<div id="main_content">
	<h2>'UR GNG 2 LV IT': Rosen College Professor Helps Attract Tourists to Ecuador</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Christine Dellert
		
		<span class="date">May 28, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 196px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="http://news.ucf.edu/resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1457/en_US/ecuador crop.jpg" height="261" width="196"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Courtesy of Manuel Rivera</p>
			
			<p>Cerro Santa Ana is a popular spot in the city of Guayaquil, where Croes hopes to attract more tourists in the coming years. </p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004106f02ced5011a120324f30350a">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:rcroes@mail.ucf.edu ">Robertico Croes</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-903-8028 </li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:mrivera@mail.ucf.edu">Manuel Rivera</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-903-8050</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette, News and Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.hospitality.ucf.edu">Rosen College of Hospitality Management</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>With its famous tortoises and lush biodiversity, Ecuador&rsquo;s Galapagos Islands attract thousands each year. About 600 miles to the southeast, a University of Central Florida professor is working to preserve another of the country&rsquo;s top natural resources -- its people.</p>
<p>Robertico Croes, an associate professor in UCF&rsquo;s Rosen College of Hospitality Management, has spearheaded a plan for the past year to double the number of visitors to Ecuador&rsquo;s Guayas province and, in turn, create more than 30,000 new jobs and generate money for an impoverished community.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s something I feel very passionately about,&rdquo; said Croes, the former minister of economic affairs and tourism in Aruba. &ldquo;Tourism is a business that will create so many opportunities for these people and bring in money for the government to give back in health care or education.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Croes&rsquo; recent master proposal to Guayas government officials includes everything from improving area signage to launching an international marketing campaign to training hundreds of service workers. He&rsquo;s also helping to develop a public-private entity with the existing tourism board to coordinate the effort and track its progress.</p>
<p>The plan should increase arrivals by half a million and boost tourism spending from about $380 million to $912 million by 2018.</p>
<p>With more than 3 million people, Guayas is the industrial &ldquo;economic capital&rdquo; of the country, local leaders say. Its capital city, Guayaquil, was a main shipping port for the Spanish empire. Today, about one of every eight people in the province is jobless, Croes said.</p>
<p>But, he adds, the warmth and heritage of the people are the main reasons why travelers come to Guayas. And it&rsquo;s only with local support that Croes&rsquo; initiatives will succeed.</p>
<p>On May 17, more than 50,000 residents, visitors and city officials gathered on Guayaquil&rsquo;s famed boardwalk, El Malec&oacute;n, to simultaneously send a text message -- &ldquo;UR GNG 2 LV IT&rdquo; -- via mobile phones to friends and family outside the country, inviting them to experience Guayas firsthand.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Our goal in creating a new brand for Guayas is to communicate to visitors and members of the local community what it means to be a part of this dynamic destination,&rdquo; said Jaime Nogales, vice president of the provincial government and head of the Guayas Tourism Board. &ldquo;Tourism is vitally important to this region, representing more than $381 million in revenue and 25,000 jobs. For travelers unfamiliar with our region, it&rsquo;s time to discover the best-kept secret in South America.&rdquo; <br />
Croes&rsquo; $130,000 contract with the provincial government to conceptualize a tourism development plan is the largest one-time grant that the Rosen College has received.</p>
<p>During the past year, Croes and his two-student team made at least a half-dozen trips to the region, sometimes inviting other UCF professors or working with local university students.</p>
<p>They visited residents&rsquo; homes and community centers, interviewed travelers in Guayaquil&rsquo;s airport, counted hotel rooms, tracked surveys and focus groups -- and even planned and participated in a beach cleanup on remote Pun&aacute; Island, where about 600 people live.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We went to their houses and talked to them, sat down in their dining rooms,&rdquo; said Manuel Rivera, a UCF doctoral student on Croes&rsquo; team and a native of Puerto Rico. &ldquo;We met so many people who will be given the chance to use tourism as a stepping stone. But they have to maintain it and make tourism a long-term plan.&rdquo;</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong><span style="font-weight: normal">The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 48,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</span></p>
		
	
